al Cycle Time Mode\\" for the fastest possible operation, \\"Accuracy Mode\\" or \\"Low Speed Accuracy Mode\\" for enhanced path precision (often used in tasks like cutting), and \\"Low Speed Stiff Mode\\" for applications requiring maximum servo stiffness, such as milling or contact tasks.\\n*   **Absolute Accuracy**: This is a calibration feature that ensures the robot\'s tool position in Cartesian coordinates is highly precise, particularly important for movements defined by Cartesian targets.\\n*   **Speed**: The velocity of the TCP, the reorientation of the tool, and the movement of any external axes are all defined by speed parameters.\\n*   **Stop Points and Zones**: Robot movements can be terminated in specific ways. A \\"stop point\\" means the robot must fully reach a specified position before proceeding. Conversely, \\"fly-by points\\" or \\"zones\\" allow the robot to round a corner without coming to a complete stop, defining a continuous path rather than a series of distinct stops.\\n*   **Triggers**: These functionalities allow robots to perform actions (like setting signals or running routines) at specific positions or times during a movement, enabling synchronized operations.",\n    "Page Number": "",\n    "URL": "projects/338431745290/locations/global/collections/default_collection/dataStores/linamar-vector-bootcamp/branches/0/documents/abb-irb140-product-specifications-pdf-p33"\n  },\n  {\n    "Document Name": "ABB_Technical_Reference_Manual \\u2014 Page 605",\n    "Full Text": "Robots exhibit several types of motion, categorized primarily by how their end-effector or tool center point (TCP) moves in space and how their joints are controlled. These motion types are crucial for different applications and are often managed through programming languages and specialized control modes.\\n\\nThe primary types of robot motion include:\\n*   **Joint Motion (Axis-wise motion)**: In this type of motion, each joint of the robot moves independently from its current angle to a target an... <truncated>
