    "excerpt": "If your robot system starts normally but you are unable to jog it manually, several factors could be at play, especially concerning the teach pendant, operational mode, or specific system errors. Here's a breakdown of common causes and troubleshooting steps:\n\n**1. Check the Operating Mode and Teach Pendant:**\n*   **Manual Mode:** Ensure the robot controller is in manual mode. Manual jogging is typically only possible in this mode.\n*   **FlexPendant Connection and Functionality:**\n    *   Verify that the FlexPendant (teach pendant) is correctly connected to the Control Module.\n    *   The joystick on the FlexPendant might be malfunctioning or deflected.\n    *   Try resetting the FlexPendant by pressing the reset button on its back. This resets the FlexPendant, not the entire controller system.\n*   **Enabling Device:** In manual mode, you must typically press an enabling device (like a hold-to-run button or a three-position device) on the teach pendant to allow manual jogging.\n\n**2. Review System Status and Event Logs:**\n*   **System Failure State (Error 10014):** If the system is in a \"System failure state,\" neither program execution nor manual jogging will be possible until the system is restarted and the underlying malfunction is addressed. You should check the event log for messages that occurred around the same time.\n*   **Execution Error State (Error 10020):** Similar to a system failure, if the program execution has stopped due to a spontaneous error, jogging might be prevented. Consult the event log for more details and remedy the fault.\n*   **Collision Triggered/Confirmed (Errors 10024, 10025):** If a collision has been triggered and confirmed, robot movement might be interrupted. If the robot was stuck, you might need to manually move it away from the object after going to manual mode.\n*   **Limit Switch Open (Errors 20201, 20217, 20218, 20219):** If a limit switch has opened, the system may go to a \"Motors OFF\" status, preventing jogging. You might need to press an \"Override Limit\" button and jog the robot back into its working area.\n\n**3. Address Jog-Specific Errors and Robot Position:**\n*   **\"Not allowed to jog with LOCAL PERS\" (Errors 20097, 20098, 20099):** These errors indicate that jogging is not permitted due to the current load, tool, or work object being defined as \"LOCAL PERS.\" You would need to change these definitions.\n*   **Robot Out of Range or Close to Singularity (Errors 50026, 50027, 50028, 50029, 50181, 50182):**\n    *   If a joint is out of its working range, use the joystick to move it back into range.\n    *   If the robot is too close to a singularity, you may need to modify the path or change to joint interpolation.\n    *   If the robot has reached a configuration limit (e.g., for the parallelogram transmission), use the joystick to move the involved joint back into the working range.\n    *   If coupled joints are out of range, use the joystick to move them back into their coupled working range.\n*   **Jog or Speed error (Error 50141):** This is a general jogging error or high-speed error. Recommended actions include jogging with incremental movement or reducing programmed speed.\n*   **Too Large Revolution Counter Difference (Error 50053):** If the revolution counter difference is too large, the robot might not be calibrated, and while manual jogging *should* be possible, it might be restricted. Updating the revolution counter and checking related hardware (resolver, cables, serial measurement board) are recommended.\n\nBy systematically checking these potential issues, you should be able to identify and resolve why your robot cannot be jogged manually.",
    "confidence": 0.95
  }
]
</pre>
