 sufficient lubrication as specified in the robot's product manual. Verify the gearbox oil level and quality.\n3.  **Inspect for Wear and Damage** If possible, disassemble the joint to measure clearance and inspect for worn or damaged components. Bearings inside motors are typically not replaced individually; instead, the complete motor is replaced if the bearings are faulty.\n4.  **Examine for Contamination** Look for any signs of contaminants in the bearing races.\n5.  **Assess Work Cycle** Evaluate if the robot's work cycle is too demanding on a particular axis. Consider programming \\\"cooling periods\\\" into the application if overheating is suspected.\n6.  **Check Mechanical Integrity** Inspect for any damage to parallel bars (if applicable) or the mechanical joint connecting the motor and gearbox.\n7.  **Verify Calibration and Settings** Ensure the robot is correctly calibrated, the TCP (Tool Center Point) is accurately defined, and revolution counters are correct, as inconsistencies here can be linked to noise.\n8.  **Brake System Check** Investigate if the brake contactor is working correctly and if the brakes on the robot axis are functioning as they should.\n9.  **Consult Documentation** Always refer to the product manual for your specific robot model for detailed instructions on handling bearings, replacing components, and recommended specifications.\n\nIt is important to address these mechanical noises proactively, as failing bearings can lead to complete joint seizure and inconsistent path accuracy, impacting production. Always observe safety information, especially when approaching potentially hot robot components.",
