<p><b>Excerpt:</b></p>
<p>If your ABB robot controller is unresponsive and the FlexPendant cannot be operated, several issues could be the cause. These range from basic power problems and physical connection faults to more complex internal hardware or software malfunctions.</p>
<p>Here are possible causes for an unresponsive robot controller and an inoperable FlexPendant:</p>
<p><b>1. Power Supply Issues:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>No power to the controller:</b> The robot controller might not be connected to the mains power supply, or the supply itself might be faulty or at an incorrect voltage level.</li>
<li><b>Main transformer malfunction:</b> The main transformer could be malfunctioning or incorrectly connected.</li>
<li><b>Tripped main fuse (Q1):</b> The main fuse (Q1) inside the Drive Module might have tripped.</li>
<li><b>Circuit breaker or contactor issues:</b> A circuit breaker (like F6) or contactor (like K41) could be malfunctioning or open.</li>
<li><b>All LEDs are OFF:</b> If no LEDs are lit on either the Control Module or the Drive Module, it often indicates a power supply problem to the system, an incorrectly connected main transformer, or issues with circuit breakers/contactors.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>2. Physical Connection Problems:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>Missing connection between Control and Drive modules:</b> The Drive Module might not start if the connection to the Control Module is incorrect or missing.</li>
<li><b>FlexPendant not connected correctly:</b> The FlexPendant itself might not be properly connected to the controller.</li>
<li><b>Damaged FlexPendant cable or connector:</b> The cable connecting the FlexPendant to the controller or its connector could be damaged.</li>
<li><b>Faulty Ethernet network:</b> Problems with the Ethernet network can prevent the FlexPendant from communicating with the controller, even if it powers on.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>3. Controller Hardware and Software Issues:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>High system load:</b> The computer system might be experiencing a high load due to overly complex programs with too many logical instructions, low I/O update intervals, or frequent communication with external PLCs or computers. This can make program execution sluggish and cause stalls.</li>
<li><b>Controller not responding (with LED indicators not lit):</b> This points to issues like the controller not being connected to the mains, a malfunctioning main transformer, a tripped main fuse, or a missing connection between control and drive modules.</li>
<li><b>Axis computer errors:</b> The status LED on the Axis computer can indicate problems, such as failure to initialize basic hardware (RED steady), missing connection to the main computer (RED long -&gt; GREEN flashing short), or a RobotWare problem in the main computer (RED short -&gt; GREEN flashing long).</li>
<li><b>Internal controller faults:</b> A permanent internal fault can be detected if a drive unit's status LED is RED steady, potentially requiring unit replacement.</li>
<li><b>RobotWare problems:</b> Errors during the RobotWare startup sequence, such as problems establishing connection to the main computer or issues with application files, can cause unresponsiveness.</li>
<li><b>Fatal non-recoverable system error:</b> An event log message like "Sys failure state active" indicates a fatal non-recoverable system error requiring a warm start (power cycling the mains switch).</li>
</ul>
<p><b>4. FlexPendant Specific Problems:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>FlexPendant completely "dead":</b> If the FlexPendant is completely without power or unresponsive, it could be due to the system not being switched on, the FlexPendant not being connected, a damaged cable/connector, or a faulty power supply from the controller.</li>
<li><b>FlexPendant starts but doesn't communicate:</b> If the FlexPendant powers on but shows no screen image or functions, it suggests issues with the Ethernet network, the main computer, or incorrect connections.</li>
<li><b>FlexPendant needs a reset:</b> Pressing the reset button on the back of the FlexPendant can sometimes resolve issues with its operation.</li>
<li><b>Hot Plug option considerations:</b> If the hot plug option is used, be aware that pressing the hot plug button disables the emergency stop on the FlexPendant. It should only be pressed when connecting or disconnecting the FlexPendant. Also, if the FlexPendant is disconnected, it cannot initiate a protective or emergency stop and should be stored out of sight.</li>
</ul>
<p>When troubleshooting, checking the LED indicators on the controller modules (Control Module, Drive Module, Axis Computer) can provide crucial diagnostic information. The ABB operating manual recommends checking power supply, connections, and then referring to LED indications for further diagnosis.</p>
</details>
