<p><b>Excerpt:</b></p>
<p>"Robot jerking" typically refers to erratic, sudden, or inconsistent movements of a robot, which usually indicates a problem or malfunction rather than an intended behavior. In a technical context, these jerky movements can stem from various causes, primarily related to mechanical, electrical, or software issues.</p>
<p>Common reasons for a robot to exhibit jerky movements include:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Brake System Malfunctions</b> Issues such as brakes not releasing correctly or faulty brakes on a robot axis can prevent smooth movement.</li>
<li><b>Electrical and Cabling Problems</b> Faulty connections, strained internal manipulator cabling, damaged insulation, or excessive electromagnetic interference near robot cabling can lead to erratic behavior.</li>
<li><b>Calibration and Configuration Errors</b> An incorrectly calibrated robot, issues with revolution counters, invalid resolver offsets, or an undefined robot Tool Center Point (TCP) can cause movement inconsistencies.</li>
<li><b>Load and Acceleration Issues</b> Incorrect load data, high acceleration values, or high external process forces can result in excessive torque on joints, leading to jerky motion.</li>
<li><b>Mechanical Wear or Damage</b> Problems like a damaged parallel bar, a damaged mechanical joint between a motor and gearbox, worn bearings, or the robot arm getting stuck (collision) can cause path inconsistency or sudden stops.</li>
<li><b>Software and Programming Errors</b> Incorrect motion configuration data, the robot operating too close to a singularity (a point where the robot loses a degree of freedom), or programmed moves that are too long for the specified speed can lead to non-optimal or jerky movements. Certain programming sequences, such as calling the SoftAct instruction twice in a row without a movement instruction in between, can also cause a jerk in the robot's movement.</li>
<li><b>Collision Detection</b> While intended for safety, sometimes collision detection can trigger and cause an abrupt stop if external forces exceed programmed limits, or if it's not deactivated when running in soft servo mode or with track motions.</li>
</ul>
<p>Troubleshooting such issues often involves inspecting cabling, checking calibration, verifying load data, examining mechanical components for damage, and reviewing the robot's programming and event logs.</p>
<p>It's important to distinguish problematic "jerking" from intentionally rapid or small movements a robot might make as part of its programmed task, particularly in applications requiring high precision or quick adjustments. However, when referred to as "jerking," it generally implies an unintended and undesirable motion.</p>
</details>Consumed 33 orchestrator stream event(s).
