mpleted.\\n*   **Verification of Safety Functions:** After completing work, verify that all safety functions are working as intended.\\n\\n**Electrical Safety:**\\n*   **Power Disconnection:** Always ensure that no one can turn on the power to the controller and robot while you are working on the system. A good practice is to lock the main switch on the controller cabinet with a safety lock.\\n*   **Qualified Electricians:** Work on the electrical equipment must be performed by a qualified electrician in accordance with electrical regulations.\\n*   **Troubleshooting:** While troubleshooting may sometimes require power to be on, the robot must be turned off (main switch to OFF) when repairing faults or disconnecting electrical leads or units.\\n*   **External Main Supply:** The main power supply to the robot must be connectable and turn-offable from outside the robot\'s working space.\\n\\n**Mechanical Safety:**\\n*   **Moving Robots are Lethal:** Any moving robot is a potentially lethal machine capable of unexpected and forceful movements that can cause serious injury or damage.\\n*   **Emergency Stops:** Emergency stop buttons must be easily accessible to quickly stop the robot.\\n*   **Working Range:** Ensure no personnel are within the robot\'s working range before starting it.\\n*   **Hot Parts:** Many robot parts, especially drive motors and gearboxes, become hot during normal operation. Use your hand to feel for radiating heat before touching and wait for hot components to cool down if they need to be removed or handled.\\n*   **Stored Energy:** Be aware of stored mechanical energy in the manipulator (for counterbalancing axes) which may be released if the robot or its parts are dismantled. Energy stored in the controller also needs consideration.\\n*   **Pneumatic/Hydraulic Systems:** All components that remain pressurized after power is off must have clearly visible drain facilities and warning signs indicating the need for pressure relief before maintenance. The pressure in these s... <truncated>
Before servicing the IRB 8700, take the following precautions:

**General Safety**
*   Only personnel trained by ABB and possessing the necessary knowledge should work on the robot.
*   Personnel under the influence of alcohol, drugs, or other intoxicating substances are not permitted to maintain, repair, or use the robot.
*   Always use suitable Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) based on a thorough risk assessment.
*   Comply with all nation/region-specific regulations and ABB Robotics instructions.
*   Unauthorized modifications to the robot are prohibited.
*   Never use the robot as a ladder.

**Electrical Safety**
*   Ensure that no one can turn on the power to the controller and robot while you are working. A good practice is to lock the main switch on the controller cabinet with a safety lock.
*   Work on the electrical equipment must be performed by a qualified electrician.
*   The main power supply to the robot must be connectable and turn-offable from outside the robot's working space.

**Mechanical Safety**
*   Emergency stop buttons must be easily accessible.
*   Ensure no personnel are within the robot's working range before starting it.
*   Be aware of stored mechanical energy in the manipulator.
*   For pneumatic/hydraulic systems, the pressure must be released before service. All components that remain pressurized after power is off must have clearly visible drain facilities and warning signs.
*   Grippers/end effectors must be designed to retain workpieces even if there is a power failure or controller disturbance.

<details>
<summary>Search Results</summary>
<p><strong>Source:</strong> ABB_IRB8700_Product_Manual.pdf</p>
<p><strong>Excerpt:</strong></p>
<p>Servicing the ABB IRB 8700 robot requires strict adherence to safety precautions to prevent serious injury to personnel and damage to the equipment. Maintenance and repair should only be performed by trained and qualified personnel who are familiar with the robot and its associated safety procedures.</p>
<p>Here are key precautions for servicing the IRB 8700:</p>
<p><strong>General Safety during Service and Maintenance:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Training and Qualification:</strong> Only personnel trained by ABB and possessing the necessary knowledge of mechanical and electrical installation/repair/maintenance should work on the robot.</li>
<li><strong>No Alcohol or Drugs:</strong> Personnel under the influence of alcohol, drugs, or other intoxicating substances are not permitted to maintain, repair, or use the robot.</li>
<li><strong>Personal Protective Equipment (PPE):</strong> Always use suitable PPE based on a thorough risk assessment of the robot installation. This includes protective gear like goggles and gloves when working with lubricants to prevent allergic reactions.</li>
<li><strong>Adhere to Regulations:</strong> Comply with all nation/region-specific regulations and ABB Robotics instructions to prevent injuries and damages during robot installation and servicing.</li>
<li><strong>No Unauthorized Modifications:</strong> Unauthorized modifications to the robot, such as welding, riveting, or drilling new holes into castings, are prohibited as they can affect the robot's structural integrity and safety. Using non-original spare parts can also negatively impact safety, and ABB is not liable for damages caused by their use.</li>
<li><strong>Avoid Climbing:</strong> Never use the robot as a ladder; do not climb on motors or other parts during service work due to the risk of slipping (hot surfaces, oil spills) and potential damage to the robot.</li>
<li><strong>Cleanliness:</strong> Ensure no loose screws, turnings, or other unexpected parts remain after work is completed.</li>
<li><strong>Verification of Safety Functions:</strong> After completing work, verify that all safety functions are working as intended.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Electrical Safety:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Power Disconnection:</strong> Always ensure that no one can turn on the power to the controller and robot while you are working on the system. A good practice is to lock the main switch on the controller cabinet with a safety lock.</li>
<li><strong>Qualified Electricians:</strong> Work on the electrical equipment must be performed by a qualified electrician in accordance with electrical regulations.</li>
<li><strong>Troubleshooting:</strong> While troubleshooting may sometimes require power to be on, the robot must be turned off (main switch to OFF) when repairing faults or disconnecting electrical leads or units.</li>
<li><strong>External Main Supply:</strong> The main power supply to the robot must be connectable and turn-offable from outside the robot's working space.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Mechanical Safety:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Moving Robots are Lethal:</strong> Any moving robot is a potentially lethal machine capable of unexpected and forceful movements that can cause serious injury or damage.</li>
<li><strong>Emergency Stops:</strong> Emergency stop buttons must be easily accessible to quickly stop the robot.</li>
<li><strong>Working Range:</strong> Ensure no personnel are within the robot's working range before starting it.</li>
<li><strong>Hot Parts:</strong> Many robot parts, especially drive motors and gearboxes, become hot during normal operation. Use your hand to feel for radiating heat before touching and wait for hot components to cool down if they need to be removed or handled.</li>
<li><strong>Stored Energy:</strong> Be aware of stored mechanical energy in the manipulator (for counterbalancing axes) which may be released if the robot or its parts are dismantled. Energy stored in the controller also needs consideration.</li>
<li><strong>Pneumatic/Hydraulic Systems:</strong> All components that remain pressurized after power is off must have clearly visible drain facilities and warning signs indicating the need for pressure relief before maintenance. The pressure in these systems must be released before service.</li>
<li><strong>Falling Objects:</strong> Watch out for falling objects when dismantling or assembling mechanical units.</li>
<li><strong>Securing Grippers:</strong> Grippers/end effectors must be designed to retain workpieces even if there is a power failure or controller disturbance. Ensure a gripper is prevented from dropping a workpiece.</li>
<li><strong>Brake Release Buttons:</strong> After service work involving the SMB recess, verify that the brake release buttons are not jammed. If a button is jammed, the affected motor brake will be released when power is turned on, which can cause serious injury or damage. Ensure the power is off, and check each button individually, adjusting alignment if necessary.</li>
</ul>
</details>Consumed 54 orchestrator stream event(s).
